üí° 3. Lessons Learned (Team Reflections)
1Ô∏è‚É£ Early Modeling Prevents Major Rework

Creating the MAS architecture early guided Unity development and avoided costly structural refactors.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Agent Communication Was More Complex Than Expected

Designing the Detection ‚Üí Analysis ‚Üí Decision ‚Üí Action flow required precise responsibility mapping.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Unity & MAS Logic Progress at Different Speeds

Unity visuals were fast to create, but integrating MAS reasoning and data flow demanded close coordination.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Time Estimates Improve With Practice

Initial tasks involving BDI modeling and anomaly mapping were underestimated, but later estimates became more accurate.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Diagrams Greatly Reduce Miscommunication

AUML sequence diagrams and state machines helped the team fully understand each agent‚Äôs behavior and interactions.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Collaboration Was Essential

Distributing work across diagrams, programming, modeling, and Unity allowed steady progress despite varying workloads.

